1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:02.895
Every agent framework has red lines.

2
00:00:02.895 --> 00:00:04.370
Don't delete files.

3
00:00:04.370 --> 00:00:06.078
Don't exfiltrate data.

4
00:00:06.078 --> 00:00:08.484
Don't run destructive commands.

5
00:00:08.484 --> 00:00:13.142
They write them in a markdown file and hope the model obeys.

6
00:00:13.142 --> 00:00:15.627
Hope is not a security strategy.

7
00:00:15.627 --> 00:00:17.102
Jake's Daily Build.

8
00:00:17.102 --> 00:00:18.189
What we built.

9
00:00:18.189 --> 00:00:19.042
What broke.

10
00:00:19.042 --> 00:00:20.207
What I learned.

11
00:00:20.207 --> 00:00:23.778
Here's the problem with prompt-based security.

12
00:00:23.778 --> 00:00:26.262
Your red lines are instructions.

13
00:00:26.262 --> 00:00:28.980
The model will usually follow them.

14
00:00:28.980 --> 00:00:29.601
Usually.

15
00:00:29.601 --> 00:00:32.473
But instructions are not enforcement.

16
00:00:32.473 --> 00:00:34.802
A sufficiently confused agent,

17
00:00:34.802 --> 00:00:36.277
a prompt injection,

18
00:00:36.277 --> 00:00:37.674
a weird edge case,

19
00:00:37.674 --> 00:00:37.907
and

20
00:00:37.907 --> 00:00:40.624
your red line becomes a suggestion.

21
00:00:40.624 --> 00:00:43.730
OpenClaw has red lines in agents dot MD.

22
00:00:43.730 --> 00:00:46.447
Claude Code has permission prompts.

23
00:00:46.447 --> 00:00:53.667
Most frameworks have some version of "please don't do bad things." All of it is prompt-level.

24
00:00:53.667 --> 00:00:55.841
None of it is deterministic.

25
00:00:55.841 --> 00:00:58.558
Today we built something different.

26
00:00:58.558 --> 00:01:01.974
A security gate that runs at the code level.

27
00:01:01.974 --> 00:01:06.787
Before the tool call even reaches the model's execution layer,

28
00:01:06.787 --> 00:01:09.659
our PreToolUse hook intercepts it and

29
00:01:09.659 --> 00:01:11.833
checks it against two lists.

30
00:01:11.833 --> 00:01:13.386
The hard block list.

31
00:01:13.386 --> 00:01:16.569
Fourteen patterns that are always denied.

32
00:01:16.569 --> 00:01:17.500
No override.

33
00:01:17.500 --> 00:01:20.838
No "are you sure?" No user approval button.

34
00:01:20.838 --> 00:01:21.925
Pipe to shell.

35
00:01:21.925 --> 00:01:23.400
Curl piped to bash.

36
00:01:23.400 --> 00:01:24.798
rm minus rf slash.

37
00:01:24.798 --> 00:01:25.186
mkfs.

38
00:01:25.186 --> 00:01:26.894
dd writes to raw disk.

39
00:01:26.894 --> 00:01:28.757
chmod seven seven seven.

40
00:01:28.757 --> 00:01:31.629
Obfuscated eval with base sixty-four.

41
00:01:31.629 --> 00:01:33.881
Writes to dot SSH or sudoers.

42
00:01:33.881 --> 00:01:36.598
These are denied at the code level.

43
00:01:36.598 --> 00:01:39.470
The model never gets to execute them.

44
00:01:39.470 --> 00:01:41.101
The trust-aware list.

45
00:01:41.101 --> 00:01:44.128
Sub-agents get additional restrictions.

46
00:01:44.128 --> 00:01:46.069
They can't run systemctl.

47
00:01:46.069 --> 00:01:47.622
They can't use sudo.

48
00:01:47.622 --> 00:01:50.029
They can't modify the firewall.

49
00:01:50.029 --> 00:01:52.590
They can't touch system crontabs.

50
00:01:52.590 --> 00:01:56.938
The parent agent can do these things with user approval.

51
00:01:56.938 --> 00:01:59.733
The sub-agent cannot do them at all.

52
00:01:59.733 --> 00:02:04.546
This matters because sub-agents run with bypassed permissions.

53
00:02:04.546 --> 00:02:07.418
They need autonomy to do useful work.

54
00:02:07.418 --> 00:02:11.145
But autonomy without enforcement is a liability.

55
00:02:11.145 --> 00:02:17.122
Our sub-agents have full tool access and zero ability to escalate privileges.

56
00:02:17.122 --> 00:02:18.520
That's the design.

57
00:02:18.520 --> 00:02:20.927
The difference between this and

58
00:02:20.927 --> 00:02:27.603
a red line in a markdown file: if a sub-agent tries to run sudo apt install something,

59
00:02:27.603 --> 00:02:32.106
the SDK returns "denied by security gate." It doesn't ask.

60
00:02:32.106 --> 00:02:34.745
It doesn't suggest an alternative.

61
00:02:34.745 --> 00:02:35.522
It blocks.

62
00:02:35.522 --> 00:02:36.919
Deterministically.

63
00:02:36.919 --> 00:02:37.773
Every time.

64
00:02:37.773 --> 00:02:40.024
Twenty-one tests verify this.

65
00:02:40.024 --> 00:02:40.956
Hard blocks,

66
00:02:40.956 --> 00:02:42.897
trust-level restrictions,

67
00:02:42.897 --> 00:02:46.002
ask-level prompts for interactive users,

68
00:02:46.002 --> 00:02:46.235
and

69
00:02:46.235 --> 00:02:48.797
clean passes for safe operations.

70
00:02:48.797 --> 00:02:49.573
All green.

71
00:02:49.573 --> 00:02:51.824
This won't stop every attack.

72
00:02:51.824 --> 00:02:52.834
Nothing will.

73
00:02:52.834 --> 00:02:57.492
But it closes the gap between "we told the agent not to" and

74
00:02:57.492 --> 00:03:02.305
"the agent cannot." That's the difference between a policy and

75
00:03:02.305 --> 00:03:04.246
an enforcement mechanism.

76
00:03:04.246 --> 00:03:07.506
Red lines in a markdown file are a policy.

77
00:03:07.506 --> 00:03:11.466
A PreToolUse hook that returns deny is enforcement.

78
00:03:11.466 --> 00:03:14.416
That's Red Lines Are Just Suggestions.

79
00:03:14.416 --> 00:03:15.114
I'm Jake.

80
00:03:15.114 --> 00:03:16.900
Catch you next episode.
